SIMPLE: inlet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inlet
<hw>In"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A passage
by which an inclosed place may be entered; a place of ingress;
entrance;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>a narrow waterway
leading into a harbor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Doors and windows, <qex>inlets</qex> of men and of light.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bay or recess, as in the shore of a sea, lake, or
large river; a narrow strip of water running into the land or between
islands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is let in or inlaid; an inserted
material.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Inlet</xex> is also used adjectively, as in
<xex>inlet</xex> pipe, <xex>inlet</xex> valve, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inlighten</ent>⟦br⟧
